## Jira Ticket Extraction

When a Jira ticket key is provided, fetch it to inform scenario design.

### Step 1 — `kubevirt-ui-mcp` memory tools (primary)

Call `get_ticket` with the ticket key. It returns: summary, status, type, labels, components, fix versions, description excerpt, and kubevirt-plugin commits that reference it — all in one call.

If the ticket is not in the cache (new ticket), call `refresh_store` to rebuild from the latest commit history, then retry `get_ticket`.

**Fallback** (if `kubevirt-ui-mcp` is unavailable):
```bash
curl -s -L "https://issues.redhat.com/rest/api/2/issue/{TICKET_KEY}"
```
- No authentication required for public CNV tickets
- Always use `-L` flag (redirects to `redhat.atlassian.net`)

### Fields to Extract

| Field | Purpose |
|-------|---------|
| **Key** | Ticket ID (e.g. `CNV-55789`) |
| **Summary** | One-line description |
| **Type** | Epic / Story / Task / Bug / Sub-task |
| **Status** | New / In Progress / Code Review / Closed |
| **Labels** | Tier tags, gating labels, release labels |
| **Components** | `CNV User Interface`, etc. |
| **Fix Versions** | Target release |
| **Description** | Full ticket description / acceptance criteria |
| **Commits** | kubevirt-plugin commits — shows what changed in the UI |

### Tier Inference from Labels
| Label Pattern | Suggested Tier |
|---------------|----------------|
| `TIER-1`, `tier1`, `gating` | tier1 or gating |
| `TIER-2`, `tier2` | tier2 |
| `cnv-X.Y.Z` | release tracking (not tier) |

### Step 2 — Existing coverage check

Always search for existing test references before designing new scenarios:
- Call `find_tests_by_jira` — returns spec files, tier, test names in structured format
- Call `get_coverage_for_feature` — broader feature coverage
- Call `search_tickets` — find related tickets by keyword
- **Fallback** (if `kubevirt-ui-mcp` unavailable):
  ```bash
  rg "CNV-XXXXX" playwright/tests/ playwright/docs/
  ```

